│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash is an assertion failure in VPTransformState::get(VPValue *Def, bool │
│ NeedsScalar). The assertion checks that when we request a single scalar value │
│ for a VPValue (NeedsScalar = true), it must be safe to do so: either VF is    │
│ scalar, the value is live-in, we have a vector value, its users require more  │
│ than just the first lane (!onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def)), or (if                    │
│ onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def)) there is exactly one cached scalar (lane 0). In the   │
│ reproducer, Def is a VPReplicateRecipe representing a replicated              │
│ getelementptr (GEP) instruction (%p.4). It was executed producing scalars for │
│ all lanes (size() == VF), but later when used by a PtrAdd VPInstruction that  │
│ only consumes the first lane, vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def) returns true    │
│ (because all users of Def only use lane 0). This violates the assertion       │
│ because multiple scalars exist while callers expect a single one.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug-only vplan log shows vector.ph and vector.body creation and the     │
│ crash occurs immediately when starting to generate vector.body instructions.  │
│ Stack trace shows VPInstruction::generate calling State.get(operand,          │
│ /*IsScalar*/ true) for PtrAdd operands (case VPInstruction::PtrAdd).          │
│ generate() for PtrAdd (VPlanRecipes.cpp:645) asserts onlyFirstLaneUsed(this)  │
│ and then forces both operands to be requested as scalars (NeedsScalar=true).  │
│ The first operand is the replicated GEP recipe. Because its users (PtrAdd)    │
│ only ever use lane 0, vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def) becomes true,           │
│ triggering the single-scalar expectation, but execution previously            │
│ materialized all lane scalars. This mismatch causes the assertion.            │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ VPReplicateRecipe::execute (LoopVectorize.cpp lines ~9475+) decides the       │
│ number of lane replicas strictly based on IsUniform, specialized store case,  │
│ or else generates all lanes. It does not take into account that although the  │
│ instruction itself is not marked uniform (IsUniform=false), all of its uses   │
│ may only require lane 0. Later vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def) relies         │
│ exclusively on user queries (PtrAdd only first lane), returning true. The     │
│ transform state then assumes there is exactly one scalar cached. Since        │
│ VPReplicateRecipe populated scalars for all VF lanes, the assertion fails.    │
│ Therefore, the generation strategy for VPReplicateRecipe is inconsistent with │
│ the consumption pattern: it should avoid generating per-lane scalars when all │
│ users only need lane 0, even if IsUniform was false.                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Modify VPReplicateRecipe::execute so that before applying the store           │
│ special-case or full scalarization, it detects the situation where all users  │
│ only need the first lane (vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(this)) and generates     │
│ only lane 0, similar to the IsUniform path. This guarantees                   │
│ Data.VPV2Scalars[Def].size()==1 when later onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def) is true.    │
│ Patch location: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp lines         │
│ 9496-9511 (inside VPReplicateRecipe::execute after handling IsUniform).       │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit diff (conceptual):                                                       │
│ --- before                                                                    │
│   if (IsUniform) {                                                            │
│     State.ILV->scalarizeInstruction(UI, this, VPLane(0), State);              │
│     return;                                                                   │
│   }                                                                           │
│   // store special case...                                                    │
│   // generate all lanes                                                       │
│ --- after                                                                     │
│   if (IsUniform) {                                                            │
│     State.ILV->scalarizeInstruction(UI, this, VPLane(0), State);              │
│     return;                                                                   │
│   }                                                                           │
│   // If all users only require the first lane, avoid generating all lanes.    │
│   if (vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(this)) {                                     │
│     // Treat as effectively uniform for code generation purposes.             │
│     State.ILV->scalarizeInstruction(UI, this, VPLane(0), State);              │
│     return;                                                                   │
│   }                                                                           │
│   // store special case...                                                    │
│   // generate all lanes                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(this) is already queried elsewhere to   │
│ decide scalar access patterns; matching generation to consumption prevents    │
│ the invariant violation in VPTransformState::get.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ Safety: This change only reduces work (fewer lane instances) when no user     │
│ needs other lanes, preserving semantics. Other paths (IsUniform true or       │
│ actual per-lane uses) remain unchanged. Store special-case still applies when │
│ needed because store users pattern differs (they may require last lane).      │
│ PtrAdd handling remains unaffected except now retrieval succeeds.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By adding a guard in VPReplicateRecipe::execute to scalarize only lane 0 when │
│ all users only use the first lane, we align value generation with consumption │
│ assumptions enforced by the assertion in VPTransformState::get. This prevents │
│ the crash for the provided reproducer and any similar pattern where a         │
│ replicated instruction has exclusively first-lane users but was previously    │
│ scalarized per lane.                                                          │
